Product Version     25.10    Cadence Design Systems, Inc.
ecoSplitFlop(25.10)                                        ecoSplitFlop(25.10)

Name
       ecoSplitFlop  -  Splits  a  multi-bit  flip-flop (MBFF) into single-bit
       flip-flops for the specified instance

Syntax
       ecoSplitFlop

       [-help]

       [-batch]

       [-force]

       [-fullSplit]

       {-inst <flopInstName> |  {{Mbff1  flopCell1}  {Mbff2  flopCell2}...}  |
       -listFile <<fileName>> | -all}

       [-legal]

       [-power]

       {-preCTS | -postCTS | -postRoute}

       [-skipRoute]

       Splits  a multi-bit flip-flop (MBFF) into single-bit flip-flops for the
       specified instance. By default, a specific flip-flop is split  only  if
       equivalent single-bit flip-flops can be found in libraries and there is
       timing  gain after the split. You can also specify that the split flip-
       flops should be placed in legal locations. By default, the positions of
       the split flip-flops are not guaranteed to be legal.

       Note:

              * This command is not controlled by the  -multiBitFlopOpt  para-
                meter  setting of setOptMode.

              * The command calls refinePlace at the end. To disable this, use
                setEcoMode -refinePlace false.

              * MBFFs must be identified by the command, reportMultibit.

              * A placeable location for the split FFs is required.

Parameters
       -help  Outputs  a  brief description that includes type and default in-
              formation for each ecoSplitFlop parameter. For  a  detailed  de-
              scription  of the command and all of its parameters, use the man
              command:  man ecoSplitFlop

       -all   When specified, splits all MBFFs into smaller-bit flip-flops in-
              cluding single-bit flip-flops (SBFFs). Only timing critical bits
              are split into single-bit flops, and the remaining, non-critical
              bits, are split into smaller bit width MBFFs, to preserve  power
              as much as possible.

              For example, a 4-bit MBFF may be split into two single-bit flops
              and one 2-bit flop.

              Note:  The -all, -inst and -listFile parameters are mutually ex-
              clusive. If the -all parameter is not specified,  one  of  these
              two parameters, -inst or -listFile, must be specified.

              Default: false

       -batch When specified, splits the MBFFs in batches.

              For example,

              ecoSplitFlop -listFile <list> -postCTS -batch -force

              Default: false

       -force Forces the flip-flop splits irrespective of timing gains.

              Note:

              * If  there  is  no timing gain and this parameter is not speci-
                fied, the flip-flops for the specified instance  will  not  be
                split.

              * If  this option is set along with the -legal option, the soft-
                ware will first look for legal locations. However,  the  flip-
                flops will be split even if no legal location is found.

              Default: false

       -fullSplit
              Forces  the  MBFFs  to  be  completely split into all single-bit
              flip-flops.

       -inst <flopInstName> | {{Mbff1 flopCell1} {Mbff2 flopCell2}...}
              Specifies pairs of MBFFs to be split and the corresponding  sin-
              gle-bit  flops to be used. You can also specify the names of the
              flop instances to be split. You can specify a single instance or
              a tcl list of instances to be split.

              Note: The -all, -inst and -listFile parameters are mutually  ex-
              clusive.  If  the  -all parameter is not specified, one of these
              two parameters, -inst or -listFile, must be specified.

       -listFile <fileName>
              Specifies the file containing pairs of MBFFs to be split and the
              corresponding single-bit flops to be used.  You  can  also  just
              specify the names of MBFF instances to be split. You can specify
              up to 50,000 instances to split. Specify each instance on a line
              and  comment  with #. Instance name should not contain spaces or
              backslashes.

              Note: The -all, -inst and -listFile parameters are mutually  ex-
              clusive.  If  the  -all parameter is not specified, one of these
              two parameters, -inst or -listFile, must be specified.

       -legal Places the split flip-flops at legal locations.

              Note: If both the -legal and -force  parameters  are  specified,
              the  software  will first look for legal locations. However, the
              flip-flops will be split even if no legal location is found.  In
              this  case,  the  split instances will be placed in the original
              location of the MBFFs.

              Default: false

       -power Splits the flip-flop for power purpose.

              Default: false

       -preCTS
              Specify this parameter, if the design stage is preCTS.

              Default: -postRoute

       -postCTS
              Specify this parameter, if the design stage is postCTS.

              Default: -postRoute

       -postRoute
              Specify this parameter, if the design stage is  postRoute.  This
              is the default setting.

              Note: One of the three options, -preCTS, -postCTS, or -postRoute
              must be specified.

       -skipRoute
              Specify if the stage is postRoute and routing is not required to
              be  performed  after  the split. Since postRoute is also the de-
              fault stage, routing is also skipped when the stage  is  default
              and -skipRoute is specified. However, for the default case, when
              the  stage is postRoute but this parameter is not specified, af-
              ter splitting the instances, routing will be called.

              Default: false

Example
              * The following command will force the flip-flop split  for  the
                instance, ff_0 during the preCTS stage:

                ecoSplitFlop -preCTS -inst ff_0 -force

              * The  following  command  will  will try to split for power all
                MBFFs during the postCTS stage:

                ecoSplitFlop -power -all -postCTS

